# Country claims and links

## Where definitions live

- **Ordinal meaning of each score** — `src/schema/index.ts` (`*_CLAIM_SCALES`, e.g. `SOCIETAL_READINESS_CLAIM_SCALES`). Do not drift from these rungs when assigning numbers.
- **Per-claim UI copy (title/description)** — `src/translations/claims.ts`. Field-level blurbs — `src/translations/schema.ts`.
- **Country evidence** — `src/countries/<country>.ts`: `ClaimData` per claim key — `score`, `text`, `links`.

## Scores

- Pick the **highest rung the evidence clearly supports**; use half-points only when the scale allows and the write-up justifies a borderline.
- Respect the parameters in narrative and when comparing to other claims’ dots.
- If evidence is weak or outdated, **lower the score** or refresh sources — do not keep a high score on stale rhetoric.

## Narrative (`text`)

- **English**, concise, tied to the **rubric level** (what politicians/media/funders actually do or say).
- Prefer **time-bounded** claims (“through 2025”, “2024 debate”) and refresh when doing a **new research pass**.
- Do not duplicate the whole bibliography in prose; **links carry sources**.

## Links (`links[]`)

Shape (`src/schema/index.ts` — `Link`):

- **`label`** — short human title (no need to repeat the full date if `date` is set).
- **`url`** — **primary** source where possible: government, parliament, regulator, official programme page, gazette. Avoid bare homepages when a deep link exists.
- **`comment`** — what the page **substantiates** (issuer, topic). Do not bury the reference period here if it belongs in **`date`**.
- **`date`** (optional) — **reference period or publication date** (e.g. `Sep 2024`, `2024–2025`, `from 2021`). Shown next to the comment in the UI; keeps dating visible without cluttering `comment`.

Use **2+ independent links** for heavily contested or high scores when practical. Mark **secondary** sources in `comment` (e.g. “NGO summary — primary: MOH”).

## Research workflow

1. Read the **claim scale** for that key in `schema/index.ts`.
2. **Search official sites** and recent parliamentary/government pages; note dates.
3. Assign **score** from evidence strength vs rubric.
4. Write **`text`** aligned with that level; avoid contradictions with links.
5. Add **`links`** with `date` split out where relevant; verify URLs load or swap for canonical equivalents.

## Public trust pillars (`PUBLIC_TRUST_*`)

Three **independent** claims — **A** clinical system (doctors, hospitals), **B** biomedical science (scientists, research, trials), **C** national health authority (ministry, PHI/CDC-style body, regulator guidance). Score each from its own evidence; do not average mentally into one number.

- **Composite mental model for longevity uptake** — the binding constraint is often the **weakest** of A/B/C for novel therapies, trials, and data programmes; say so in `text` or `comment` when one pillar lags.
- **Sources** — prefer repeated representative waves: Wellcome Global Monitor; Eurobarometer (science & tech, health); national panels (e.g. Pew US); national health barometers. Edelman is usable as **supporting** context, not the sole basis for C (government trust ≠ ministry-of-health trust).
- **`date` on links** — survey wave or field period when the figure is cited (e.g. `2023`, `Sep 2024`).
- **Not** `QUACKERY_RESISTANCE` — high institutional trust can coexist with large alternative-medicine markets.

## Aging media framing (`AGING_MEDIA_FRAMING`)

Evidence is **national mainstream media and mass science communication**, not parliament minutes or ministry strategy pages (those belong under **legislative salience** / **policy commitment**).

- Prefer **major newspapers**, **public broadcasters** (BBC, NHK World, NOS, SR, etc.), and **named science desks**; link the **article or programme page**, not only homepages.
- **Rung 2** — lifestyle, prevention, dependency/care, demography, and disease targets (dementia, CVD) without aging-as-unified-biology as a recurring frame.
- **Rung 3+** — repeated **popular** treatment of **biological aging** (clocks, hallmarks, senolytics, organ/biological age) in outlets with general audiences; outreach NGOs or podcasts count only if the URL is a **stable, citable** page.